04659nam a22007455i 9780231555630DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021047783  a97802315556307 a10.7312/gree204662doi  a(DE-B1597)626408  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aJQ1681b.G74 2022 4aJQ1681b.G74 2022 7aPOL0540002bisacsh04a306.20952223/eng/202112061 aGreen, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLine of Advantage :bJapan’s Grand Strategy in the Era of Abe Shinzō /cMichael Green. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Asia in the World0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNo other country has devised a grand strategy for managing China’s rising economic and military power as deliberately or successfully as Japan. Seeking to counter Chinese ambitions toward regional hegemony, Japan has taken an increasingly assertive role in East Asia and the world. During the tenure of Prime Minister Abe Shinzo, the country pursued closer security cooperation with the United States and other democracies, established a more centralized national defense system, and advanced rules and norms to preserve the open regional order in the Indo-Pacific that is crucial to its prosperity and survival—all while managing an important economic relationship with China.In Line of Advantage, Michael J. Green provides a groundbreaking and comprehensive account of Japan’s strategic thinking under Abe. He explains the foundational logic and the worldview behind this approach, from key precedents in Japanese history to the specific economic, defense, and diplomatic priorities shaping contemporary policy toward China, the United States, the two Koreas, and the Indo-Pacific region. Drawing on two decades of access to Abe and other Japanese political, military, and business leaders, Green provides an insider’s perspective on subjects such as how Japan pursued competition with China without losing the benefits of economic cooperation. Assessing the strengths and weaknesses of Japan’s new active role, Line of Advantage sheds new light on a period with profound implications for the future of U.S. competition with China and international affairs in Asia more broadly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGeopoliticszIndo-Pacific Region. 0aPolitical leadershipzJapan. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Asian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/gree2046640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555630/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishb2022  a978-3-11-099451-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishb2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2022  aZDB-23-PLWb2022